🚨 Subnet Update 🚨

Hey @graphite・43,

We’ve heard the chatter and concerns around mining on our subnet. While we’ve been heads down building a product we’re proud of, we recognize that we need to match that same energy in growing and supporting our community. Transparency is key — and we want everyone to know: we’re not just listening, we’re acting.

We’re excited to share that we’re teaming up with @consτ [τ, τ] to overhaul the entire subnet mechanism and build something much stronger for the long term. Here’s the new framework we’ll be rolling out:

1️⃣ Ridges Model – Miners will submit their algorithms to an open-source competition. Each epoch, we’ll release the top-performing algorithms so the entire network can continue to iterate, improve, and compete.

2️⃣ Incentives for the Best – Instead of emissions going to everyone, rewards will focus only on the top miners across problem sets and clusters, ensuring real competition and performance-based incentives.

3️⃣ Benchmark First – We’ll focus on beating academic benchmarks and positioning this subnet as the algorithmic solution subnet on Bittensor.

⚡ For existing miners: You’ll have 1 week to wind down your services. After this period, 100% of miner emissions will be burned while we focus on implementing the overhaul. ( ⏳ Emissions burn begins: Friday, October 10, 2025 7:00:00 PM (10/10/2025 7:00 PM) )

We’re incredibly excited about this new direction, and we believe it will set the foundation for something groundbreaking. Thanks to @consτ [τ, τ] for being with us in the exciting building journey ahead, and thanks to the community for always being with us, and we hope you'll stick around.

Very excited about this also. For one, we hope to stimulate open innovation where everyone here can participate without a steep learning curve — you’ll be able to read the top solutions and try to improve them. There shouldn’t be any UID pressure and registration will be normal and transparent. 

The team can also stably monetize the results with privacy, and then later build a closed source sub mechanism via integration with other subnets on Bittensor like Targon or Chutes.

There is also the aspect to this where Graphite’s problem is easily cut into smaller problems which miners can try to focus on. Then more so, the whole field of algorithmic design is really open to us here, with sub mechanisms able focus on a variety of architectures. 

Props to @Sherwin | Graphiτe | SN43 [τ, ע] for making this happen

Yup, definitely quite a bit of work from here. We’re working tightly with Const and bouncing off design considerations for the entire miner and validator flow

The initial design is very simple. 

1. Miners write a python script (it could be adapted to any language later). The script has a start up function (init method) and a set of methods that can be called like “solve_tsp”.

2. Miners upload the script as a public GitHub gist

3. Validators pull the scripts and run them in a docker container with tools pre installed for you. 

First iteration probably is just a pure winners take all. Then likely @Sherwin | Graphiτe | SN43 [τ, ע] works with you guys to get all the desired tools, languages, and infra available to the running scripts. 

For instance “you now have access to a GPU of this type” or “you have a sqlite database you can populate at initialization”.

As i understand it the vision from Sherwin is to break the TSP landscape up into a set of sub regions (similar to what he was trying to do with the current design) — allowing miners to focus on problems within specific size ranges.

At first like all changes it will be crazy and exploited. But if the team moves fast I’m very hopefull.

Thanks for explaining the idea. Getting it to work for an algorithmic SN like this would be very valuable, but it's not easy. There are more hurdles imo compared to evaluating agents or ML models.

- You will have to sandbox the solve_tsp code *a lot*. Small example: it would be forbidden to call an API that offloads the calculation or run obfuscated code. How will this be detected? One can do checks by an LLM (like in chutes) but this will become a game of whack-a-mole for the devs 🤕 

- Performance of TSP solvers (like much of scientific compute) is very dependent on the hardware (cores, RAM & cpu speed). Validators will need to run almost identical CPU systems to get a good estimate of the *true* score of an algorithm in statistical sense. Breaking the validation up into subproblems makes the estimation only more difficult (more variance, Pareto optimality, ...)

- State of the art algorithms in TSP are very complex, sometimes rely on existing code (for example LP solvers), and in compiled code. 

Even getting this to work in Python only is a major accomplishment. It will likely not beat state of the art in TSP but it might be useful as a blueprint for bittensor. The devs have a lot of work to do ... 😝

On a principle level, what is the value of a miner that optimizes a hyperparameter in a winning code and takes top place (even beating it with epsilon treshold). 99% of code is the same but it is objectively better. Does he deserve to win all? (I don’t know.)

You need to increase the accuracy of your evaluation through sampling so that you know with precision that a miner performance is X.XX acc or score 

Then you can reward them for beating the previous guy 

If they don’t win by some margin then you don’t give them the win 

This saves you from copiers (implementation details are important ) since if you copy a model you never beat the threshold on the previous winner (same algorithm)

You will need a lot of samples to accurately determine a winner, given how heteregenous the evaluation is here (different HW of validators, subproblems / sizes, TSP solvers are very sensitive to initial starts, ...). Luckily, generating and evaluating large TSP problems is cheap and easy. It wouldn't be bad to involve miners when designing an evaluation system with so many hyper parameters, except for the obvious COI :-p
If the variance exists you can also query all miners for every problem
